{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"17ca88bb-a708-41ec-8c98-2dff6a694829","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";C:\\Users\\ContainerUser\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n### 5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 6. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\nThen open at [speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't in the container, use the [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) sidecar instead — it exposes a REST API for trace collection without modifying the app container.\n- For **EventPipe**-based CPU profiling, `--profile cpu-sampling` captures stack samples at ~10ms intervals, which is usually sufficient to identify hot paths.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"64dbacaf-5313-40e2-9ecf-b0686ec34811","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a troubleshooting/knowledge question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":470,"requestId":"7842:8A8EB:1CE3304:2027719:69FA97FB"},"id":"1373fdd3-28c8-4068-b2ee-79e4dbd8fe1e","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:23:17.367Z","parentId":"8060d622-443a-4732-b26b-2f94dd82b15b"}
